Gamification is a popular pedagogical approach in computer science education, and advances in large language models (LLMs) enable dynamic and engaging learning experiences. Storytelling is an age-old practice in which narratives can be used in education to communicate learning objectives in entertaining ways. With the use of LLMs, both games and stories can be dynamically customized to fit a student's learning needs. In this PhD dissertation work, gamification and storytelling are being studied alongside artificial intelligence (AI) to create educational games and tools that will encourage and motivate students to learn. Three educational games have been created, each involving LLMs in unique ways. The first game, ''Engin-AIR-ing'', examined the use of AI-generated quiz questions in a flipped classroom of undergraduate students (N=23). The results showed an increase in quiz scores of the students who used the game. The second game, ''Quack the Code'', researched the effectiveness of learning by teaching an AI-powered debug duck in a game show atmosphere. The results showed that the students who engaged with the game (N=25) found it helpful. The third tool, ''Bytesize Stories'', looked at the use of storytelling as a teaching method and specifically with a K-12 audience (N=30) in hopes of increased participation. The results showed that most students improved their knowledge after using the tool. In all three studies, the results suggest that generative AI and the use of games and storytelling can enhance student engagement and learning.